04817nam a22007455i 9781501717550DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017175507 a10.7591/97815017175502doi  a(DE-B1597)503476  a(OCoLC)1038488443  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD9146.I44K477 1998 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a334/.68371/0954831 aFranke, Richard W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy at Work in an Indian Industrial Cooperative :bThe Story of Kerala Dinesh Beedi /cPyralal Raghavan, Richard W. Franke, T. M. Thomas Isaac. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 map, 2 drawings, 10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell International Industrial and Labor Relations Reports00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote On The Spelling Of Indian Place-Names -- tCHAPTER ONE. Beedi Workers And The Kerala Model -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Making Of The Beedi Working Class -- tCHAPTER THREE. Solidarity Versus Retrenchment: The Birth Of KDB -- tCHAPTER FOUR. From Mobilization To Efficiency: The Role Of The Central Society -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Dynamics Of Shop Floor Democracy: Empowerment Versus Supervision In The Beedi Primary Cooperatives -- tCHAPTER SIX. Efficiency And Profit In The Primary Societies: KDB's Market Dilemma -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. KDB And The International Movement For Workers7 Cooperatives -- tAFTERWORD. Tobacco Production And Diversification At KDB -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors tell the story of a democratic workers' cooperative that makes hand-rolled cigarettes, known as "beedis," in the unorganized sector of a fiercely competitive capitalist economy in India. For decades, beedi workers have been among the most exploited and impoverished of India's work force. In 1969, in the southwestern Indian state of Kerala, several thousand workers banded together to form a worker-owned beedi cooperative. The authors argue that their skill and determination, combined with Kerala's generally leftist political culture, allowed them to beat the odds. The cooperative surprised the private sector beedi barons by creating an enterprise that has lasted and prospered, offering the best wages and benefits in the business, while making a profit and contributing to the local economy.The authors analyze the major features of the cooperative, assessing its overall structure, worker-elected management, shop floor democracy, and progress in providing a better life for its worker-owners. Tensions are also discussed, including the complaints of women workers and the need for diversification from tobacco.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aIsaac, T. M. Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRaghavan, Pyralal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171755040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501717550.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL 